value.value: A cell that is specialised to accumulate a particular substance(s).
Any cell that is capable of some oxygen transport.

A cell derived from the specialized ectoderm flanking each side of the embryonic neural plate, which after the closure of the neural tube, forms masses of cells that migrate out from the dorsal aspect of the neural tube to spread throughout the body.
A mesenchymal cell in embryonic development found in a contracting mass and that gives rise to osteoprogenitors.
A cell found within the adrenal medulla that secrete biogenic amine hormones upon stimulation.
A neural precursor of the central nervous system.
An early neural cell developing from the early ependymal cell of the neural tube.
A precursor of the central nervous system that gives rise to glial cells only.
Any animal cell containing pigment granules.
A pigment cell that is capable of detecting light stimulus that is involved in visual perception.
A mesenchymal cell that is part of a small mass of condensed mesenchyme in the enamel organ; it differentiates into the dentin and dental pulp.
A specialized mesenchymal cell that resides in the dermal papilla located at the bottom of hair follicles. This cell plays a pivotal roles in hair formation, growth, and cycling.

definition.value: Are these really all stem cells?

value.value: A cell of the sclera of the eye.
A structural cell that is part of optic choroid.
Any cell that is part of some extraembryonic structure.
Any extraembryonic cell that is part of some amnioserosa.

An extraembryonic cell that develops from a trophectodermal cell. This cell is found in the outer layer of the blastocyst and can invade other structures in the uterus once the blastocyst implants into the uterine wall. A trophoblast cell is involved in the implantation of the embryo into the uterine wall, placental formation, remodelling of maternal vasculature in the uterus, nutrient and gas exchange, hormone production, and immune modulation to support fetal development.
A cell of the outer layer of a blastula that gives rise to the ectoderm after gastrulation.
An undifferentiated cell produced by early cleavages of the fertilized egg (zygote).
A multifate stem cell found in skeletal muscle than can differentiate into many different cell types, including muscle. Distinct cell type from satellite cell.

definition.value: Multi-potency demonstrated ex vivo.  At the time of writing, it is unclear whether the endogenous population differentiates into multiple cell types in vivo.

value.value: A smooth muscle cell that is part of a sphincter. A sphincter is a typically circular muscle that normally maintains constriction of a natural body passage or orifice and which relaxes as required by normal physiological functioning.
A smooth muscle cell associated with the vasculature.
A cell of the early embryo at the developmental stage in which the blastomeres, resulting from repeated mitotic divisions of the fertilized ovum (zygote), form a compact cell mass.
A cell of the embryo in the early stage following the blastula, characterized by morphogenetic cell movements, cell differentiation, and the formation of the three germ layers.
An epithelial cell of the integument (the outer layer of an organism).
Diploid cell produced by the fusion of sperm cell nucleus and egg cell.
The cell protoplasm after removal of the cell wall.

An epidermal cell that is part of a cell cluster organ of the insect integument (such as a sensillum) and that secretes a cuticular specialization that forms a socket around the base of a cuticular specialization produced by a trichogen cell.
A progenitor cell found in the larval epidermis of insects and that gives rise to the adult abdominal epidermis.

An epidermal cell that is part of a cell cluster organ of the insect integument (such as a sensillum) and that secretes a cuticular specialization, often in the form of a hair, bristle, peg or scale. The base of this specialization is often surrounded by a socket produced by a closely associated tormogen cell.
The support cell that makes the thecogen dendritic cap - a cuticle-like matrix around the tip of the eo-dendrite and which encloses the soma of the eo-neuron.
A cell that is part of a scolopidium and surrounds the dendrite of a scolopidial neuron.
A precursor of mature hemocytes.
